Italy brings Europe to a dark hour

By Lee ming-ja

PUBLISHED: March 16,2020

On the morning of March 8, The Sun was blocked by dark clouds over Milan, the capital of the Lombardy region in northern Italy. The minimum temperature dropped to 3.6 c, while it began to rain in Rome in the south. The cold and humid conditions are said to be the most suitable for transmission of the new coronavirus. On that day, the new coronavirus also began to spread in 93 cities across Italy.

As of 1800 hours on March 9,9,172 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in Italy, with a total of 724 cases cured and 463 deaths, making Italy the country with the highest number of deaths outside China. At the same time, the spread of the epidemic has accelerated across Europe, with Italy at the center. Some people say that Europe has become Hubei, and Italy is the "Wuhan of Europe. ".

Italian Prime Minister Contes announced on the evening of the 9th, from the 10th will be implemented in a nationwide lockdown. All residents are not allowed to enter or leave the city at will, except for work, emergencies or medical conditions. Meanwhile, all sporting events are suspended across the country. School suspension extended to 3 April. RT television called the move "unprecedented" .

However, the Italian "siege" and the Chinese siege is not exactly the same. The Cherry blossoms are in full bloom in Milan, and though the streets are not as busy as they used to be, locals can still be seen strolling, walking their dogs, drinking coffee, as if nothing had happened and continuing to enjoy life. "after the closure of the city, the restaurants and bars were still open, so the locals went, " said Wu Jie, editor-in-chief of the milan-based newspaper New European overseas Chinese. "although people can not go to other cities, they can move around inside the city. ".

"All of us have to give up something for the benefit of Italy, " Contes said in his speech, "We have to make this decision now, and it can only be done if we all work together to adapt to these stricter measures, " Contes said in an interview with Italian media, he himself has been pondering the words of British Prime Minister Winston Churchill during the Second World War: "This is our darkest hour, and we will do it. "

The case fatality rate is at a record high

According to the latest data, the mortality rate of patients with new coronary pneumonia in Italy is above 5.04% , which is the highest in the world. The mortality rate of new coronary pneumonia is far higher than 2.3% in China and 2.9% in Hubei province.

Faced with the outbreak, the Italian government is not too late. It was the first country to announce restrictions on Chinese air travel since the new outbreak of pneumonia in Wuhan. Prime Minister Contes declared a state of emergency on January 31st, when Italy first confirmed two imported cases of new coronary disease. Contes then announced that he was suspending all non stop flights to and from China. However, about four-fifths of passengers opted for a connecting flight rather than a direct one in 2018, according to information on preferred flights.

"By declaring a state of emergency, the government has the legal right to resort to temporary emergency measures in exceptional circumstances without parliamentary approval, " explained Sun Yanhong, deputy research fellow at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and secretary-general of the Italian studies branch of the European Society of China, the Italian government declared a state of emergency, to be precise, "national health emergency. ".

Although Italy was one of the first countries outside China to take preventive measures, "But it was too late to stop the spread of the infection and containment measures could not stop the local spread, " replied Benjamin Cowling, a professor of epidemiology and biostatistics at the public health of the University of Hong Kong.

The silence of Italy was finally broken on a Friday night. On February 21st Italy discovered its own "patient number one" , a man from the city of cordoo in Lombardy  LombardiaReg. who was described by the media as a "social butterfly" . The family doctor, who was first diagnosed with flu when symptoms were first reported on Feb. 14, has also been diagnosed with a new crown infection. Since then, the patient has infected his pregnant wife, a friend who ran with him and three friends who met at a bar. More than 50,000 residents were affected when the government sealed off more than a dozen nearby towns.

Experts at Sacco Hospital in Milan isolated the new coronavirus on February 28. It is believed that the new coronaviruses appearing in Italy "are a new variant virus" . The head of the team, Masim Gally, told AFP that the new coronavirus had been running unknowingly for weeks before the official diagnosis in Italy, "probably as early as mid-january in the Italian Peninsula" . So far, Italy has not found the virus to "patient one" "patient zero.

"Many scholars believe that local follow-up of patient No. 1 is not timely and early migration has not been followed, and that Italy needs extensive testing for mild cases, " Adalia, a senior scholar at the Johns Hopkins University, told China Newsweek.

The first patient spent 36 hours in a hospital in the city of cordoo before being diagnosed and quarantined, and medical staff complained that the hospital did not issue a warning immediately after the patient was diagnosed, with delays of "as long as several hours. " Exposing health care workers to the risk. Italian prosecutors and police have been sent to the inspection team to investigate.

"The increase in the number of confirmed cases has been accompanied by an increase in the number of cures, and the majority of deaths are among the elderly, which may have contributed to the early underestimation of the epidemic by the local population, " Wu Jie said. In response, ageing-stricken Italy began urging "people over 75, people over 65 with health problems, to reduce social activity" . According to Italy's National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China, there are 1.5 times as many people over 65 as there are under 14.

"It is very important to protect vulnerable populations against NCV, " said Zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of the Public Health at the University of California, Los Angeles. "The focus should be on protecting people 60 years of age or older. The United States is doing the same. " Young people are less likely to become seriously ill, more likely to be mild, and sometimes have the same symptoms as a cold, with a relatively low mortality rate. At the same time, in the epidemic process, young people can also produce their own immune antibodies, improve the level of group immunity, in the late epidemic, the epidemic will be suppressed.

Young Italians are not required to "segregate" their homes and see crowds on the streets, "I feel that many people are not aware of our situation, " Italian virologist Roberto Jlio de Figueiredo Brioni wrote in a facebook post on March 4. "Too quiet news coverage has led citizens to underestimate the problem. "

On March 1st Contes, Italy's Prime Minister, signed a decree dividing the country into three parts according to the severity of the outbreak. The earliest outbreak of the town as a "red zone, " residents are not allowed to leave the city, all public activities were cancelled, schools closed, museums and other cultural sites were closed. All medical staff in the "yellow zone" around the red zone will be suspended from work; gatherings, sports and other competitive activities will be suspended; schools will be closed for a week; cinemas and Discos will remain closed; Reopen the museum and cafes, restaurants, and bars where food delivery services can be provided, but the museum requires that visitors keep a distance of more than one meter. The rest are normal areas.

Italy's Health Ministry has issued 10 epidemic prevention recommendations that put "frequent hand-washing" at the top of the list, even cautioning that "made-in-china products and packages are not dangerous" and that "pets can not spread the new coronavirus" , it also recommends "wearing a mask only if you suspect you are sick or are helping a patient. ". On February 26th an asymptomatic MP was jeered for entering parliament wearing a mask.

Mask or no mask

On the afternoon of January 25, Wang Wanru returned to Milan after a holiday trip. He had just got off the plane and immediately found the airport pharmacy and bought 50 masks. A friend texted her: You can't buy masks in the city of Milan, they're going up to 5 euros a pop. "At that time, I thought I would be prepared, but I didn't expect to use it so soon, " Wang Wanru told China Newsweek.

The threat of the new coronavirus was not felt on the streets of Milan in late January, as people went out drinking, partying and dancing. "The locals took the outbreak seriously after patient number one showed up. The man was young, not an old man with what is commonly known as poor resistance. The man deteriorated and was transferred to intensive care, where he has since been discharged,"Wu Jie recalls.

When news of patient one spread, parts of the local supermarket in Milan were snapped up. Wang Wan ru impression, out of stock is not only disinfection water, and Pasta and meat paste, but over the weekend, the supermarket shelf soon completed. At that time, there are local GRANDPA wearing gloves to purchase, cashiers see Wang Wan ru mask will mumble two "virus, coronavirus. ". "Most Chinese people wear masks when they go out, " Wang said, adding that the price of the masks had risen to 10 euros.

Zheng Zaisheng, president of the italian-chinese Youth Federation in the central city of Florence, also faces a difficult choice between wearing a mask or not. Florence, the capital of Tuscany, had its first case on February 25, with 23 confirmed cases so far.

Zheng wearing a mask to the supermarket or shopping malls, will cause the local people look askance, he felt uncomfortable, he took off the mask and put it in his pocket. Fear of contagion on the one hand, and stigma on the other. Local Chinese have been stressing the need to travel less and suspend work and school. Currently, about 1,300 Chinese immigrants in the Tuscan region are voluntarily quarantined at home.

Marche International Chinese School, founded by Wenzhou Native Li Jiayue and his wife, is in the central Italian region of Marche, home to more than 40,000 ethnic Chinese. The school has been closed since the beginning of February due to the emergence of new coronary pneumonia and has been teaching online since 24 February. At the time, many local Italian schools were still open, and students who were home on leave for fear of infection had to present a doctor's note to the school.

Local Italians, by contrast, do not seem to care about the new crown. A white-haired man smiled and asked, "what are you afraid of? " A grandmother in her 80s clapped her hands, "I'm an old man. When I'm buried, I die. When I die, I die. good-bye. " The young merchandise worker said he was "strong and young, so I won't be infected. " Some people just say, "it's the flu, hygiene is good enough, stop, people are scared because they're stupid. " "You only need to wear a mask if you have symptoms. "

"Italians believe that only people who are sick wear masks and that washing your hands is better than wearing masks. And since you're sick, you're less likely to go out, so it's not necessarily discrimination for locals to walk around people wearing masks,"Ning Zhiyuan, a Chinese artist who has lived in Italy for eight years, told China News Weekly, his city was not in the red zone, he worked from home after the outbreak, had only a few shopping trips, and he did not wear a mask.

There are also legal reasons for the local resistance to face masks. In 1975, Italy enacted a national anti-terrorism law that strictly prohibits the wearing in public of any clothing, mask or device that may conceal the face, and offenders face fines and imprisonment. In 2005, the Italian Senate has passed a series of anti-terrorism legislation that raises the penalty to a maximum of two years in prison and a fine of 2,000 euros.

"I don't support the public wearing masks, it's not the right public health measure, " Adalia said bluntly. "Masks don't work on the general public and should be reserved for those who need them. " Panic buying of face masks could lead to a shortage of hospitals.

The reality is that Italy is now "hard to find" . Before the suspension of direct flights between China and Italy, overseas Chinese from Wencheng County, Wenzhou, arranged a total of more than 100,000 face masks. The last flight from Milan to Wenzhou was sent to China to fight against the epidemic. "Now, in turn, Wencheng County's overseas Chinese Association and Shanghai Wencheng Chamber of Commerce are raising money to donate masks to us, " Zhou Bin, President of the Overseas Chinese Restaurant Association in northern Italy, told China News Weekly.

Unlike China, Italy "has a relatively small population density and is less prone to human-to-human transmission of droplets, " although new Crown Infections in early, mild cases are still contagious. "epidemic prevention measures should be adapted to local conditions, " said Zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of the Public Health at the University of California, Los Angeles. "In the end, all roads lead to the same destination. "

Even with the city shut down, the orange wars will continue

By February 23, the total number of confirmed infections in Italy had doubled to 152, but the small town of Ivrea, in the stricken Pyrmont region, went ahead with its annual "orange wars" for three days, this is the culmination of Carnival in Ivrea.

"We know the risks we are taking, but the carnival means a lot to us, " one local who attended the event said in a video interview, adding that few people were wearing masks. One of the world's oldest festivals dates back to Medieval Times in Europe. According to statistics, affected by the epidemic, the number of participants than in previous years, the day about 15,000 people gathered "streaking" a day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A man and a woman kiss through a mask at Milan central railway station in the Italian region of Lombardy on March 8. Photograph by Daniele Mascolo

Meanwhile, Italy's central government imposed traffic restrictions in more than a dozen municipalities and suspended classes for a week in the regions of Lombardy  LombardiaReg. And Veneto, which reported the largest number of reported cases. Local students were told to parade in groups to celebrate the fall-from-the-sky holiday.

On the fourth day of Lombardy  LombardiaReg.'s "curfew" , a petition was filed by owners of bars, clubs and discos, the city of Milan lifted a ban on bars and other entertainment venues from operating after 6 pm on February 26. Bars that reopen are required to "control the flow of customers as much as possible. " Guests are not allowed to eat at the bar, and must be escorted to the table by a waiter, and are required to keep a distance of more than one meter.

"It's in the nature of Italians to be free-spirited, to be casual about a lot of things, and to get together and talk. But I personally think that in the past two weeks, the awareness of the new coronavirus in the Italian health authorities and the political arena has been obviously somewhat confused. The lack of consensus on how to prevent and control the epidemic and the lack of proper publicity to the public have also been an important reason for the huge difference in actions between different regions and the escalation of the epidemic,"Sun said.

However, Wu Jie, editor in chief of the new European Journal OCTA, disagrees. Italian Prime Minister Contes, a lawyer by training, has already used public health and infectious disease experts authorized by parliament to guide the prevention and control of the epidemic, "The political system and the health system speak with one voice, " Wu Jie said.

The lack of a unified approach across Italy has to do with the structure of its national governance system. Italy is divided into 20 districts, 98 provinces and 8,099 municipalities. It is a four-level State Administration system of the province of central Florida. The powers and responsibilities of different levels of government are clearly defined by law. For example, the central government is responsible for state-level affairs, such as diplomacy, and after the establishment of the regional system, it enjoys legislative power, focusing on public services such as health care and education, while provincial and municipal governments are responsible for specific livelihood work such as economic development, science, technology and culture.

"Each region can adjust to its own circumstances and need not be in full compliance with the Prime Minister's decree, " Wu Jie explained, noting that the central Marquette region had ordered the closure of all schools in the region at the time of the zero diagnosis, the central government has also criticized the suspension of schools in the region as premature and detrimental to students'learning.

Such as the imposition of curfews and the re-lifting of curfews in Lombardy  LombardiaReg. Bars, which appear to swing from side to side, "It's really about keeping the economy going, " Dong Jinyi, a former Chinese ambassador to Italy and Switzerland, told China News Weekly, "from the central to the local, they are actually seeking a balance between epidemic prevention and economic development. "

The provinces and towns that were eventually sealed off in Italy were concentrated in the northern Lombardy  LombardiaReg. , the Veneto and the Emilia region of Florida, the most densely populated and economically developed region in the country. Lombardy  LombardiaReg. , for example, has a GDP per head of about 30 per cent higher than the rest of the country, the second highest in the region, according to Eurostat in 2017.

Tens of thousands of hotel bookings and flights have been cancelled following the outbreak in Milan, the regional capital of Lombardy, and Venice, a popular tourist destination in the Veneto. Lucca Patani, president of the Italian Tourism Federation, estimates that tourism, the mainstay of the Italian economy, will suffer about 7.4 billion euros in losses by the end of May.

"In the near future, the number of visitors will be almost zero. Even if the virus goes away this summer, the industry will not return to normal soon,"Roberto Jlio de Figueiredo Perrotti of the Bocconi University in Milan told BBC News. One consequence of Italy's long slump is that the government is financially stretched, with total debt equal to 133% of GDP. In the EU, only Greece exceeds that figure.

Chinese restaurant owners, teased by the Italian media for not taking a holiday on New Year's Eve, were finally forced to take annual leave in groups under the influence of the epidemic. "Thousands of chinese-owned restaurants in Milan, including Chinese, Japanese and Italian, are basically closed, " Zhou Bin, President of the Overseas Chinese Restaurant Association in northern Italy, told China News Weekly.

Following the outbreak in China, "due to ignorance and fear of the new coronavirus, Chinese restaurants are suffering from a drop in the number of customers, " Alessandro, a Democratic Congressman from Milan, wrote on facebook on February 2. Although Italian virologists have repeatedly stated that coronaviruses are not transmitted through food, data from TheFork, an Italian restaurant reservation platform, show that as of January 20,2020, orders for Chinese food booked on the platform fell 43 per cent in two weeks. On the morning of the Lantern Festival on February 8, Sarah, the mayor of Milan, made a special trip to the Chinatown community to meet residents and have breakfast together.

Three days after the outbreak in Italy, Zhou Bin's restaurant began to close, until now. He calculated a loss of 500 to 600 euros per day, including the market rent and the wages of the employees. However, if the business were to open, it would lose more than 2,000 euros per day due to low passenger flow, material losses and expenses such as water and electricity consumption. A Chinese bar next to the restaurant is still struggling, with a daily income of 60 to 70 euros, less than 1 / 15th of normal.

At this time of year, the restaurant season is supposed to be filled with daily Italian diners from around Milan and local Chinese, as well as buyers for fashion week, furniture shows and tourists from around the world. Zhou bin originally anticipated that this year would be the 50th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and Italy. According to Zhou's knowledge, orders from another nearby Chinese restaurant, which can host banquets and celebrations for more than 100 people, had all been canceled from February to June.

"Now it's not only Italians who don't come to Chinese restaurants, but we don't dare to go to Italian restaurants because they don't wear masks, " said Zheng, who is now largely isolated at home and occasionally goes out to pack food for home, his florence-based Import and export business has not been shut down, and employees have been quarantined from their homes and working online, but orders have been cut by less than half due to the outbreak.

Roberto Jlio de Figueiredo Perrotti, a professor of economics at the University of Bocconi in Milan, estimates that Italy's GDP will almost certainly shrink in the first quarter and technically fall into recession, with GDP falling for two consecutive quarters, it may even shrink throughout the year.

"small family businesses may survive, but larger restaurants and businesses are hard to sustain, " Zhou said, recalling that there were fewer than 50 of Milan's 600-plus Chinese restaurants after SARS in 2003, "This time it could be worse. Whether we survive it or not depends on how business is doing in the first few months after the epidemic is over, " Zhou said. "The government's tax cuts should be implemented as soon as possible. "

Medical resources are in short supply

The Lancet, an international medical journal, published its latest ranking of quality and accessibility in 195 countries in 2019, targeting 195 countries and territories, italy ranks in the top 10 in terms of quality and accessibility of care, calculated from 32 assessment indicators, an advantage in Italy's response to the new coronavirus. In addition, Italy's universal health care, day-to-day care costs little money.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical workers check the body temperature of each person entering a hospital in the northern Italian city of Pavia, Lombardy  LombardiaReg. , On March 3.

But faced with a concentrated outbreak of the disease, Italy's medical resources are still somewhat stretched. Most hospitals in northern Italy have suspended emergency and general surgery to save medical resources and make room for more beds, while the Italian military hospital opened a new dedicated wing on March 4, to meet the hospitalization needs of patients with new coronary pneumonia. "At this rate of growth, we won't last a week. The hospital's empty beds can be counted on both hands, and the medical system can not continue to function in such a situation,"Italian anesthesiologist and president of the Association of Critical Care Doctors Vigaro told Italian Radio Internationale on March 4.

Benjamin Cowling, a professor of epidemiology and biostatistics at the public health at the University of Hong Kong, said it was impossible to intercept the new coronavirus completely, but the only way to slow its spread was to stagger the onset of the disease as much as possible, so that the medical establishment can withstand the pressure. Benjamin warned that the new coronavirus spreads rapidly, although the majority of patients with mild illness, but still 10% to 15% of patients will enter serious illness, and recovery period is long, once patients enter serious illness, need to spend considerable medical resources and personnel. Big cities such as Milan and Bologna will run out of medical resources, and the consequences will be unimaginable.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medics work in a tent set up outside a hospital in Brescia, Italy, on March 3. Photo / Xinhua

"Italy is now in the early stages of the epidemic, perhaps similar to Wuhan in early or mid-january. Their health care system will face more pressure in the next one to two months,"Benjamin Cowling, a professor of epidemiology and biostatistics at the public health of the University of Hong Kong, wrote in an email to China Newsweek.

Lin Jingjing, an undergraduate in Bologna, booked a flight home on March 14. "I was afraid of being infected, and I was afraid that I would not be treated in time because of the limited medical resources, so my family insisted that I go home first. " She will be transferred from Frankfurt Airport, France, landing Shanghai Pudong International Airport, then sent by staff of the Qingtian County government to send her back to the county quarantine point for 14 days quarantine.

Zhou Bin, who is in Milan, has no plans to return to China. He and more than 20 other employees of the restaurant are in isolation in their homes. According to Zhou, there are more than 50,000 Chinese living in Milan, and 80 percent of them live in Wenshang. The largest number comes from Wencheng County, where there are more than 30,000. As far as he knows, no one has yet been infected with the new coronavirus.

In the "closed city" order issued, calm Italian people also began to flee the "epidemic area. According to La Repubblica, the Milan central station and Garibaldi Gate Station's night trains were full of people with luggage and more than 500 people scrambled to board the last train to southern Italy, at least 150 people are waiting to buy tickets at the box office in the hope of leaving Lombardy  LombardiaReg. Before the blockade takes effect. Some of the residents, who live temporarily in the south of Milan, have fled by car for fear of being stranded there.

Italy's Health Minister Roberto Speranza said violators could face up to three months in prison and a fine of 206 euros. Those who are known to have contracted the virus and have escaped from the quarantined area or are still participating in social activities will be severely punished in accordance with the Criminal Law.

As of 12:00 GMT on March 9,28,165 cases had been confirmed in 104 countries and regions except China. With the rapid spread of new European crown disease, more than 20 European countries have confirmed cases, Italy, Germany, France, Spain and other countries have more than 500 confirmed cases.

On the afternoon of March 8, Chief of the Army Staff Falliner of Italy issued a statement saying he had tested positive for the virus nucleic acid and was being quarantined in his home. The website of the Portuguese Presidential Palace reported on the 8th that Portuguese President De Sousa   Had met students in the school with a confirmed case of new pneumonia, will voluntarily accept two weeks isolation, cancellation of all scheduled official activities. Portugal added 9 new cases on August 8, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 30. Floden, deputy governor of Sweden's Central Bank, tested positive for the virus, Reuters reported.

Who director-general Tan Desai said at a regular briefing on the epidemic on 9 March that the current spread of the disease in more than 100 countries and regions has become a very real threat of a pandemic.
